{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532379"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:26:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:26:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14673"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14673"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.07,0.67,0.17,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101647"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7366"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14673"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84088"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5581"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34759"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101647"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with persistent headache following a minor head injury three days ago whilst playing football with friends. He has type 1 diabetes mellitus and uses an insulin pump. He had a splenectomy and right foot amputation following a motor vehicle accident in childhood and uses a prosthetic limb. He works as a welder and recently got a decorative tattoo on his arm one week ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination is unremarkable. The treating team is considering magnetic resonance imaging of his brain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most significant contraindication to MRI for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Splenectomy","Recent tattoo","Metal fragments in eyes","Prosthetic limb","Insulin pump"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen considering MRI safety, the most important consideration is the presence of ferromagnetic materials that could potentially move or heat up in the magnetic field, causing serious injury. Given this patient\u0027s occupation as a welder, the risk of metallic foreign bodies in the eyes is significant. Welders are at particular risk because microscopic metal fragments, known as \u0027ocular foreign bodies\u0027, can be propelled into the eyes during grinding, cutting, or welding, often without the person being aware. These fragments can remain asymptomatic and undetected for years, but exposure to the strong magnetic field of an MRI can cause them to move, leading to catastrophic ocular injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore patients at risk of having\u003Cstrong\u003E metal fragments in eyes\u003C/strong\u003E have a contraindication to MRI and require orbital X-rays to exclude metallic foreign bodies before MRI scanning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecent tattoo\u003C/strong\u003E (less than two weeks old) is only a relative contraindication to MRI. While there is a theoretical risk of burns or irritation due to metallic pigments in tattoo ink, this risk is generally low and can be managed with close monitoring and patient education.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplenectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not a contraindication to MRI as no metallic objects are typically left in the body after this procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProsthetic limb\u003C/strong\u003E can be safely removed before MRI scanning and is therefore not a contraindication. The patient should be asked about any retained metallic hardware from the amputation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin pump\u003C/strong\u003E should be removed before MRI scanning and is only a relative contraindication. Modern insulin pumps are designed to be removable and the patient can temporarily disconnect it during the scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in MRI safety screening is to maintain a high index of suspicion for potential ferromagnetic materials, particularly in patients with relevant occupational exposures or trauma history. When in doubt, appropriate imaging (such as orbital X-rays) should be performed to exclude metallic foreign bodies before proceeding with MRI.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ferromagnetic objects in or on the body are absolute contraindications to MRI scanning.","Occupational exposure to metal particles, such as in welders, requires orbital X-rays before MRI to exclude metallic foreign bodies.","Recent tattoos and removable prosthetics are only relative contraindications to MRI scanning."],"references":["MRI Safety Guidelines Version 3.0, The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Radiologists. 2021.  Available at: https://www.ranzcr.com/college/document-library/mri-safety-guidelines","Hargreaves B, Worters P, Pauly K, Pauly J, Koch K, Gold E. Metal-Induced Artifacts in MRI. American Journal of Roentgenology. 2011:197 (3).  Available at: https://ajronline.org/doi/10.2214/AJR.11.7364"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84088"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14673"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84088"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-03T16:03:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-03T16:04:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7366"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101647"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":